benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/admin/cache/accounts/{accountId} - Invalidates Caches per account level

covered: Valid Deletion: TC01 confirms 204 with empty body and caches for accountId are invalidated
Non-Existent Resource: TC02 returns 404 when accountId does not exist
Invalid accountId input formats: TC03 (invalid format), TC12 (abcd), TC14 (SQL injection), TC15 (XSS) validate input validation
Authorization: TC05 and TC06 verify 401 for missing/expired tokens
Degraded performance / service unavailability: TC07 (204 or 503) and TC08 (503) verify handling under load or cache service down
Query parameters: TC09 ensures extra query parameters do not break deletion and returns 204 with empty body
Very large or max-length accountId: TC10 validates behavior (404/400)
Unsupported HTTP methods: TC11 confirms 405 when using GET on this endpoint
Regression and backward compatibility: TC12 and TC19 verify old UUID patterns and current endpoint behavior
Performance and concurrency: TC13 validates concurrent deletions and response times
Security validations: TC14 (SQL injection) and TC15 (XSS) ensure accountId is sanitized
Edge cases: TC16 no accounts -> 404; TC17 transient network recovery -> 204; TC18 partially populated DB -> 404
Backward compatibility: TC19 ensures no regression vs previous delete endpoint usage
gaps: Race condition testing for concurrent deletion of the same account (same-resource race condition) is not covered
Authorization gap: no test for 403 Forbidden when the user is authenticated but not an admin
Rate limiting / throttling scenarios are not covered
Caching headers for DELETE responses (e.g., Cache-Control, ETag) are not tested
500 Internal Server Error scenarios (e.g., database failure) are not explicitly tested
recommendations: Add a test for 403 Forbidden by simulating an authenticated non-admin user and ensure proper error handling
Add a race-condition test that performs concurrent DELETE requests against the same accountId to validate synchronization and idempotency
Introduce rate-limiting/throttling tests (e.g., many parallel DELETE requests) and verify appropriate 429 responses or throttling behavior
Add tests to validate caching headers on DELETE responses if caching is applicable (Cache-Control, ETag) or explicitly document their absence
Add a test simulating a 500 Internal Server Error scenario (e.g., DB failure) and verify proper 500 handling and logging
Consider documenting or testing a 403 scenario for insufficient permissions even if current tests use admin credentials
